answers.body_markdown:
You set the font size of &amp;lt;h1&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;h2&amp;gt; relative to the font size of the surrounding text, and you compute the padding in ems to be the same as the padding of &amp;lt;p&amp;gt;.

  For example:

  ```
  body { font-size: 24px; }
  p    { padding-top: 1em; }
  h1   { font-size: 1.25em;
         padding-top: 0.8em; /* = 1 / 1.25 */
       }
  ```

The visual gap will still be different because you have not said anything about margins and line-heights.

Check out how it works (note how 0.5 = 0.625 / 1.25):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;style&gt;
      p, h1 { border: 1px solid red; }
      p { padding-top: 0.625em;
          padding-bottom: 0.625em; }
      h1 { font-size: 1.25em;
           padding-top: 0.5em;
           padding-bottom: 0.5em; }
      span { background: #DDEEFF; }
    &lt;/style&gt;

